Experiment 1(9): Perform various GIT operations on Local and Remote Repositories
Step 1: Check Git Installation
git --version (checks whether git is installed)
Step 2: Configure Git (Only Once)(for every experiment run this)
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"
—for local Repositories—-
Step 3: Create a Local Repository
mkdir exp1 (create a folder on desktop)
Open cmd in that folder
git init
Step 4: Create a File
echo "This is experiment 1" > file1.txt
Step 5: Check Repo Status
git status
Step 6: Add File to Staging
git add file1.txt 

Step 7: Commit the File
git commit -m "Added file1 for experiment 1"
(you can check new file will be added in the folder)

—for remote Repositories—-
Step 8: Add Remote Repository
(You must create a new GitHub repo → copy URL)
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo.git
Step 9: Push to GitHub
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
Step 10: Pull New Changes From GitHub
git pull origin main











Experiment 2(11): Pull files from GitHub, Modify them, and Push back using Git
Create a folder where you want to pull and open cmd in that folder
Step 1: Clone Repository from GitHub
git clone https://github.com/username/repo.git
(the repo will be which project you want to pull)
Step 2: Move into the Repository
cd repo
Step 3: Open a File & Make Changes
Example:
echo "New line added by Bhumika" >> notes.txt
(you can open a file or makes changes in the existing file)
Step 4: Check Status
git status
Step 5: Add Changed Files
git add notes.txt
Step 6: Commit Changes
git commit -m "Updated notes.txt with new content"
Step 7: Pull Before Push (Important!)
git pull origin main
Step 8: Push Changes to GitHub
git push origin main
(you can see new file will be pushed in the project)






Experiment 3: Execute Basic Git Commands(14)
 Basic Git Commands List
Make a folder and open cmd in it
 1. Check Git Version
git --version
2. Initialize Git Repository
git init
3. Check Status
git status
4. Add File
(before run this command [echo “my message” > filename])
git add filename
5. Add All Files
git add .
6. Commit Files
git commit -m "Your commit message"
7. Add Remote URL
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo.git
(first create a repo and take the url)

8. Check Remote URL
git remote -v
9. Push to GitHub
git push origin main

10. Pull from GitHub
git pull origin main
11. Show Commit Log
git log
12. Create & Switch Branch
git branch dev
git checkout dev








Experiment 4: Create Repository → Add File → Commit → Push to GitHub
Step 1: Create New Folder
Create a folder and open cmd in it
Mkdir exp4
Cd exp4
Step 2: Initialize Git
git init
Step 3: Create a New File
echo "Experiment 4 file" > test.txt
Step 4: Add the File
git add test.txt
Step 5: Commit the File
git commit -m "Added test.txt for experiment 4"
Step 6: Create New GitHub Repository
Go to GitHub → New Repository → Copy HTTPS URL.
Step 7: Add Remote Origin
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/exp4.git
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/Madhura281/myrepository.git

Step 8: Set Branch & Push
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
